   "title": "Module 1 · Differentiation from First Principles",
   "html": "$$f'(x)=\\lim_{h\\to 0}\\dfrac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h}$$<p>Apply the formula, simplify, then let $h\\to 0$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Find $f'(x)$ if $f(x)=x^2$ from first principles.",
     "a": "$\\dfrac{(x+h)^2 - x^2}{h} = \\dfrac{2xh + h^2}{h} = 2x + h$. As $h\\to 0$: $f'(x)=2x$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Rules of Differentiation",
   "html": "<ul><li>Power rule: $\\dfrac{d}{dx}(x^n) = nx^{n-1}$.</li><li>Constant rule: $\\dfrac{d}{dx}(c) = 0$.</li><li>Sum rule: derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives.</li></ul>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Differentiate $y=3x^4 - 5x^2 + 7$.",
     "a": "$\\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 12x^3 - 10x$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Integration & Area",
   "html": "$$\\int x^n\\,dx = \\dfrac{x^{n+1}}{n+1} + C\\ (n\\ne -1)$$<p>The area under $y=f(x)$ between $x=a$ and $x=b$ (where $f\\ge 0$) is $\\int_a^b f(x)\\,dx$.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Evaluate $\\int (2x+3)\\,dx$.",
     "a": "$x^2 + 3x + C$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Find the area under $y=x^2$ from $x=0$ to $x=2$.",
     "a": "$\\int_0^2 x^2 dx = [x^3/3]_0^2 = 8/3$ square units."
    }
   ]
  }
